tors’ and Officers’ Liability: Comparative Report -- tList of Contributors and Editors -- tPublications -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years several cases concerning the liability of directors and officers have courted controversy. Arguments raised in such discussions oscillate between two extremes: on the one hand, the need for governing bodies to give a space to entrepreneurial discretion and on the other hand to ensure the protection of investors in and creditors of a company from the consequences of disadvantageous decisions by those bodies. In light of the geographical dispersal of the above stakeholders, the study offers a comparative insight into the liability of directors and officers in 10 key European jurisdictions (in particular, Austria, Czech Republic, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Spain and Switzerland) and 4 non-European jurisdictions (namely Brazil, Israel, Turkey and the United States). Amongst other things it investigates existing company law principles on the topic and examines their interaction with tort law and other fields with a view to suggesting principles for better stakeholder protection. National reports are complemented by an economic analysis and insurance, conflict of laws and comparative reports. The study also benefits from case study analyses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCorporate governancexLaw and legislation. 0aDirectors of corporationsxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aExecutives' liability insurancexLaw and legislation. 0aTort liability of corporations. 4aSchadenersatzrecht. 7aLAW / Torts.2bisacsh  aTort Law.1 aCabrelli, D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeakin, S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul